<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-268-551  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 268 551.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  Jan 9 1989 v10 n2 p20(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>All sides see ONA shining in post-divestiture mire. (open networkarchitecture)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kellner, Mark A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Everyone seems to agree that the one good thing that came out ofthe AT andamp; T divestiture is the FCC's Open Network Architecture(ONA).andP;  ONA will allow telecommunication companies to sharenetwork architectures in the form of basic service elements.andP;  Thiswill give other firms the chance to develop new telephone servicesthat they can market to customers.andP;  ONA will provide the means tomake them available without the worry of cross-subsidies and such.andO;Some worry, however, about who will govern access to ONA elements.andO;Observers see problems happening if stronger companies preventweaker ones from gaining equal access.andP;  It was theDavid-and-Goliath battle between MCI and AT andamp; T that led to thecourt divestiture.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Network ArchitectureTelecommunicationsTelephone CompaniesUnited States. Federal Communications Commission.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>